{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}} '''Brian Taylor''' (born 9 January<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b00txhjg/Brian_Taylors_Big_Debate_01_10_2010/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130419174642/http://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b00txhjg/Brian_Taylors_Big_Debate_01_10_2010/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2013-04-19|title=Reveals on his Big Debate programme he is nine days younger than Alex Salmond, placing his date of birth as 9 January}}</ref> 1955 in [[Dundee]]) is the [[political editor]] for [[BBC Scotland]]. Taylor &ndash; who joined the BBC in 1985 &ndash; originally co-presented ''Left, Right and Centre'' and was political correspondent prior to his current role. Taylor has covered politics on television since the [[United Kingdom general election, 1979]].
In 2009, he presented ''Holyrood and the Search for Scotland's Soul'', a documentary by ''[[BBC Scotland Investigates]]'' to mark the 10th anniversary of the [[history of Scottish devolution|devolved]] [[Scottish Parliament]].
==Early life== Taylor attended the independent [[High School of Dundee]] and graduated from the [[University of St Andrews]] in 1977 with an [[Master of Arts (Scotland)#Honours|MA (Hons)]] degree in [[English studies|English]].<ref name=Taylor1>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/correspondents/briantaylor/ | work=BBC News | title=Brian Taylor | date=5 March 2012}}</ref> Following his graduation, Taylor was employed as a [[journalist]] by the [[Aberdeen]]-based [[Press and Journal (Scotland)|Press & Journal]] before a six-year spell as a lobby correspondent at [[Westminster]].
==The BBC== Taylor joined [[the BBC]] in 1985, co-presenting the [[BBC Scotland]] political programme ''Left, Right and Centre'' with [[Kirsty Wark]], and presenting ''[[Good Morning Scotland]]''. Following this, he was appointed political correspondent and then political editor.
Taylor has written two books on Scotland's new [[Scottish Parliament|Parliament]]: ''The Scottish Parliament'' (Polygon, Edinburgh University Press, 1999), an account of the road to devolution and its consequences; and ''Scotland's Parliament: Triumph and Disaster'' (Edinburgh University Press, November 2002), analysing the early years of the new Parliament.
==Personal life== Taylor is married with two sons.<ref name=Taylor1 />
Taylor is a keen [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] football supporter and attends games regularly. He has presented the club's inaugural Hall of Fame dinner on a number of occasions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dundeeunitedfc.co.uk/index.asp?tm=34#|title=DUFC Hall of Fame Dinner|publisher=Dundee United FC|access-date=24 September 2008}}</ref>
He was awarded an honorary degree by [[Abertay University]] in 2010. <ref>https://www.abertay.ac.uk/life/alumni-and-supporters/honorary-graduates/brian-taylor/</ref>
Taylor joined Twitter in 2012 and has yet to tweet anything.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/tannadicelad?lang=en|title=Brian Taylor (@TannadiceLad) - Twitter|author=|date=|website=Twitter.com|access-date=5 October 2017}}</ref> His lack of tweets has made him a Twitter icon who people regularly joke has said something outrageous then deleted it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/patricksmith/tannadice-lad|title=How BBC Scotland's Politics Editor Became A Cult Hero On Twitter Without Ever Tweeting|author=|date=|website=Buzzfeed.com|access-date=5 October 2017}}</ref>
