{{Administrative divisions of Sri Lanka}}

In [[Politics of Sri Lanka|Sri Lanka]], [[province]]s ({{lang-si|පළාත|translit=Paḷāta}}; {{lang-ta|மாகாணம்|translit=Mākāṇam}}) are the first level [[administrative division]]. They were first established by the [[United Kingdom|British]] rulers of [[British Ceylon|Ceylon]] in 1833. Over the next century most of the administrative functions were transferred to the [[Districts of Sri Lanka|districts]], the second level administrative division. By the middle of the 20th century the provinces had become merely [[ceremonial]]. This changed in 1987 when, following several decades of increasing demand for a [[Devolution|decentralization]], the [[Thirteenth Amendment to the Constitution of Sri Lanka|13th Amendment]] to the [[Constitution of Sri Lanka|1978 Constitution of Sri Lanka]] established [[Provincial councils of Sri Lanka|provincial councils]].<ref name="Law 2010">{{cite web|url=http://www.statoids.com/ulk.html|title=Provinces of Sri Lanka|last=Law|first=Gwillim|year=2010|work=statoids.com|accessdate=19 January 2010}}</ref><ref name=PC>{{cite web|title=Introduction|url=http://www.priu.gov.lk/ProvCouncils/ProvicialCouncils.html|work=Provincial Councils|publisher=[[Government of Sri Lanka]]|accessdate=16 January 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090707214924/http://www.priu.gov.lk/ProvCouncils/ProvicialCouncils.html|archivedate=7 July 2009|df=}}</ref> Currently there are nine provinces.

==History==
===Anuradhapura Kingdom===
{{See also|Anuradhapura Kingdom}}
[[File:1000pxancien trisinhalaya-locator-map svg.png|200px|thumb|left|[[Maya Rata]], [[Rajarata|Pihiti]] & [[Ruhuna]]]]
{{clear}}

===British Ceylon===
{{Politics of Sri Lanka}}
{{See also|Kingdom of Kandy|British Ceylon}}
After the British took control of the entire island of Ceylon in 1815 it was divided into three ethnic based administrative structures: Low Country Sinhalese, Kandyan Sinhalese and Tamil. In 1829 the British established the [[Colebrooke–Cameron Commission]] to review the colonial government of Ceylon, including its administrative structures.<ref name=LoC>{{cite web|title=The Colebrooke-Cameron Reforms|url=http://www.country-data.com/cgi-bin/query/r-13139.html|work=Sri Lanka|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|accessdate=16 August 2009}}</ref> The Commission recommended that the existing three ethnic based administrations be unified into a single administration divided into five geographic provinces.<ref name=LoC/> Accordingly, on 1 October 1833 five provinces under one administration came into being:<ref>{{cite book|last=Mills|first=Lennox A.|title=Ceylon Under British Rule 1795–1932|year=1933|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]/[[Humphrey S. Milford]]|location=London|page=68|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A3BCAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=16 August 2009}}</ref>{{Sfn|Mendis|1946|p=39}}<ref name=DN210303>{{cite news|last=Samarasinghe|first=L. M.|title=River basins as administrative divisions|url=http://archives.dailynews.lk/2003/03/21/fea01.html|newspaper=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)]]|date=21 March 2003}}</ref><ref name=TN>{{cite web|title=Sinhala Colonisation in the Hereditary Tamil Regions of the Island of Sri Lanka|url=http://www.tamilnation.co/unitednations/uncom00c.htm|work=UN Commission on Human Rights 56th Sessions: March/April 2000|publisher=Tamil Nation|accessdate=16 August 2009}}</ref>

* [[Central Province, Sri Lanka|Central Province]] – composed of the central Kandyan provinces.
* [[Eastern Province, Sri Lanka|Eastern Province]] – composed of the maritime districts of Batticaloa and Trincomalee, and the Kandyan provinces of Bintenna and Tamankaduwa.
* [[Northern Province, Sri Lanka|Northern Province]] – composed of the maritime districts of Jaffna, Mannar and Vanni, and the Kandyan province of Nuwara Kalawiya.
* [[Southern Province, Sri Lanka|Southern Province]] – composed of the maritime districts of Galle, Hambantota, Matara and Tangalle, and the Kandyan provinces of Lower Uva, Saffragam and Wellassa.
* [[Western Province, Sri Lanka|Western Province]] – composed of the maritime districts of Colombo, Chilaw and Puttalam, and the Kandyan provinces of Three Korales, Four Korales, Seven Korales and Lower Bulathgama.

Over the next fifty years four additional provinces were created, taking the total number to nine:<ref name=DN210303/><ref name=TN/><ref>{{cite news|last=Karalliyadda|first=S. B.|title=Independence Struggle for a Hundred and Thirty Three Years|url=http://archives.dailynews.lk/2009/02/04/inde.asp?id=s11|accessdate=16 August 2009|newspaper=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)]]|date=4 February 2009}}</ref>
* [[North Western Province, Sri Lanka|North Western Province]] was created in 1845 from northern Western Province (districts of Chilaw, Puttalam and Seven Korales).{{Sfn|Mendis|1946|p=51}}
* [[North Central Province, Sri Lanka|North Central Province]] was created in 1873 from southern Northern Province (district of Nuwara Kalawiya) and north-western Eastern Province (district of Tamankaduwa).{{Sfn|Mendis|1946|p=84}}
* [[Uva Province]] was created in 1886 from parts of Central Province, Eastern Province (district of Bintenna) and Southern Province (district of Wellassa).{{Sfn|Mendis|1946|p=84}}
* [[Sabaragamuwa Province]] was created in 1889.{{Sfn|Mendis|1946|p=85}}

===Sri Lanka===
[[File:Sri Lanka North Eastern Province locator map.svg|200px|thumb|left|The short lived [[North Eastern Province, Sri Lanka|North Eastern Province]]]]
The number of provinces remained static until September 1988 when, in accordance with the [[Indo-Sri Lanka Accord|Indo-Lanka Accord]], [[President of Sri Lanka|President]] [[J. R. Jayewardene|Jayewardene]] issued proclamations enabling the Northern and Eastern provinces to be one [[Administrative division|administrative unit]] administered by one elected Council, creating the [[North Eastern Province, Sri Lanka|North Eastern Province]].<ref name=DM171006>{{cite news|last=Selvanayagam|first=S. S.|title=North-East merger illegal: SC|url=http://archives.dailymirror.lk/2006/10/17/front/02.asp|newspaper=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=17 October 2006|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403231109/http://archives.dailymirror.lk/2006/10/17/front/02.asp|archivedate=3 April 2013|df=}}</ref> The proclamations were only meant to be a temporary measure until a [[referendum]] was held in the Eastern Province on a permanent merger between the two provinces. However, the referendum was never held and successive Sri Lankan presidents issued proclamations annually extending the life of the "temporary" entity.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sambandan|first=V. S.|title=Sri Lanka's North-East to remain united for another year|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/2003/11/14/stories/2003111411881500.htm|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=14 November 2003}}</ref> The merger was bitterly opposed by Sri Lankan [[nationalists]]. On 14 July 2006, after a long campaign against the merger, the [[Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna|JVP]] filed three separate [[petitions]] with the [[Supreme Court of Sri Lanka]] requesting a separate Provincial Council for the East.<ref name=DM171006/> On 16 October 2006 the Supreme Court ruled that the proclamations issued by President Jayewardene were null and void and had no legal effect.<ref name=DM171006/> The North-East Province was formally de-merged into the Northern and Eastern provinces on 1 January 2007.

Sri Lanka currently has nine provinces, seven of which have had provincial councils from the start.<ref name=PC/>
